<text id="1298" date="2011-01-19" length="short" lengthw="186" duration="short" durations="71.0" speed="medium" speedwm="157.2" delivery="read" topic="Politics" topicspec="Conclusions of the European Council meeting on 16 17 December" type="English interpretations" comments="NA">
<speaker name="Gualtieri Roberto" gender="M" country="Italy" politfunc="MEP" politgroup="SD">
<st language="it" length="short" lengthw="141" duration="short" durations="70.0" speed="slow" speedwm="120.9" delivery="read">
<interpreter id="EN119" gender="F" native="Y">
<s id="1298:1" video="http://amelia.sslmit.unibo.it/video/video.php?id=1298&start=00.00.09&end=00.00.20">
Ehm thank you President of the European Council , I see 2 problems with regard to the t- ehm the nature of Article 136 , o- o- one is institutional , political .
</s>
<s id="1298:2" video="http://amelia.sslmit.unibo.it/video/video.php?id=1298&start=00.00.20&end=00.00.37">
Article 3 of the Treaty on the Functioning defines the monetary policy of ehm the euro countries as being part of the exclusive competence of the Union , get Article under Article 2 it sets out exclusive competence can be ehm exercised by countries if authorised by the Union .
</s>
<s id="1298:3" video="http://amelia.sslmit.unibo.it/video/video.php?id=1298&start=00.00.37&end=00.00.45">
It is therefore difficult to see why the application of a ehm rule that has been defined by the Treaty requires to be ehm for- reformed .
</s>
<s id="1298:4" video="http://amelia.sslmit.unibo.it/video/video.php?id=1298&start=00.00.45&end=00.01.03">
Then there is a political problem : ehm the choice of the procedure to reform the Treaty , rather than making use of Article 2 or Article 352 or 136 ... ehm puts the future of the euro into the hands of 26 processes of ratification .
</s>
<s id="1298:5" video="http://amelia.sslmit.unibo.it/video/video.php?id=1298&start=00.01.03&end=00.01.12">
Is there any awareness of the fact that if even one process of ratification would ehm fail , it would be difficult at this point to come up with a B plan for the euro ?
</s>
<s id="1298:6" video="http://amelia.sslmit.unibo.it/video/video.php?id=1298&start=00.01.12&end=00.01.19">
Is the European Council aware that the choice of this procedure has ehm placed the future of the euro in a state of risk ?
</s>
</interpreter>
</st>
</speaker>
</text>
